Commentary.Commentary: Welcome back, folks! The New Zealand players have gathered near the fence and are in a huddle. Out walk Alex Lees and Zak Crawley to open for England. The hosts would be aiming to bat once, bat big and bat New Zealand out of this Test match. For that to happen, they will need a foundation and let's see how their openers deal with the new ball. Tim Southee to begin proceedings...
... SECOND INNINGS ...

New Zealand recovered slightly after Lunch, but the huge damage done in the morning session will have its effect throughout this Test match. Thanks to the knocks of Southee and de Grandhomme, they avoided the embarrassment of bundling out under 100, but it is still peanuts if you consider the batting record at this venue. The Kiwi bowlers will have to put their best foot forward to keep themselves relevant in this Test. Stay tuned for England's reply...

A commanding bowling show from England! They shot out New Zealand in under two sessions and will be brimming with confidence. It's a cracking start to Ben Stokes' captaincy, and when you have bowlers of the quality of Anderson, Broad and the new addition Potts, you have very little to do as captain. A word of praise for Matthew Potts who picked up four wickets on his debut. He showed great control over his art, and it was a bit unfortunate that he picked up a calf injury and didn't get the chance to put his name on the Lord's honours board.

OUT! TAKEN! That is a soft dismissal! Boult had one ball to negotiate and he fails to do so. Stokes gets the last man. On middle, a slower one. It holds on to the surface. Boult chips it towards mid-wicket. Ollie Pope dives to his right and takes it. The frustrating stand for England comes to an end! NEW ZEALAND BOWLED OUT FOR 132!
Commentary.Howout: c Ollie Pope b Ben Stokes

Commentary.Commentary: Outside off, this is guided through point for one.
A slower one outside off, Colin looks to drive but is beaten.
Fuller and on off, Colin hits it to covers.

Not sure what Boult was waiting for there! On the pads, Colin looks to flick, it goes off the leading edge through point. They take one. Colin is off for a second but Boult is holding his ground. He goes for it in the end. The throw is well above the keeper. Had it been straight to Foakes, there could have been a chance at the other end.
Two! Fuller and outside off, this is pushed through covers for a couple.

FOUR! Stand and deliver! That is superb from Boult. He is not going to back down. Fuller and outside off, this is lofted over the cover fielder and into the fence. The number 8 for Rajasthan is showing his worth with the blade.
Shorter and outside off, Colin chops it to point for a single.
Really good fielding! But three added to the total. These are vital runs for the Kiwis. Fuller and on off, this is pushed down the ground. Broad from mid on, chases, dives and keeps it down to three.
Once again Colin de Grandhomme is happy to take the ones! Outside off, this is guided through point for one.
Robin Das goes off now, seems Stuart Broad has returned.
Two, good running! Good length and on middle, Colin works it with soft hands through mid-wicket. Two taken.
On middle, defended.
Not a good ball to end! Down the leg side. Boult does not fiddle with it.
Fuller and outside off, Boult tries to heave but misses.
Outside off, not played at.
A good slower one outside off, Boult slashes at it but misses.

Matthew Potts is leaving the field. He clutched his calf muscle after the last ball and Ben Stokes doesn't want to take any chance with him. Potts exits and the English skipper will complete this over. The hosts have three substitutes on the field now, Harry Brook for Jack Leach, Robin Das for Matthew Potts and Craig Overton for Stuart Broad, who at the moment is sitting on the fence.
Length again and on off, Boult pushes it to covers.
That is a stylish leave! Outside off, not played at.
FOUR! England won't mind that as it will bring Boult on strike! Shorter and outside off, Colin guides it past point and it races away to the fence.
Really good shot. Very clever! Short and on middle, Boult upper cuts it over the slip cordon. Does not go all the way but three taken.
Outside off, left alone. Two more balls for Boult to negotiate.
Colin is happy to take the single! Length and on off, Colin pushes it towards covers for one.
On off, Colin de Grandhomme defends it well.
Gets off the strike on the first ball! Plays that one awkwardly! Angled into the pads, he works it by taking one hand off the handle, through square leg for one.
Two taken which means Boult will be on strike for the next over! Shorter and on middle, this is pulled through mid-wicket for two.
Three! Boult is off the mark! Fuller and on middle, this is chipped past the bowler, it goes down the slope and three runs taken.
Another one on off, this is pushed to covers.
Boult makes a little bit of room this time, he is followed, and this is bowled on his body. Defended.
Length and on off, Boult guides it to point.

Trent Boult walks in next at number 11. He consistently batted at 8 for Rajasthan in the recently concluded Indian T20 League and would be feeling demoted. A good chance for him to showcase his batting prowess.

OUT! LBW! Matthew Potts returns and strikes in no time. Not sure why he was kept out of the attack for so long. This is on a length, outside off, it lands and jags back in. Patel misses as he tries to defend and gets hit on the back thigh. A huge appeal and the finger is raised. Ajaz takes the DRS quickly but this time it has not come to his rescue. No bat there and it's hitting the leg stump. Potts has 4, he has 5 balls to bowl at the last man. Can he get his 5th?
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Matthew Potts

Commentary.Commentary: Matthew Potts is back on now!  He is two shy of picking a fifer on Test debut, that too at Lord's.
Outside off, on a length. Left alone.

FOUR! What a shot that is and the 100 is up for the Kiwis! Looked farfetched at one stage but the counter-attacking cricket after the break has helped them get there. They would love a few more. This is full and on middle, Colin whips it nonchalantly over mid-wicket and for a boundary.
Some issue with the ball and the umpire agrees! The box of balls comes out.
Good length and on off, defended.
Two more! Fuller and around off, Colin de Grandhomme strokes it through covers for two.
Just about clears Stokes! Fuller and on off, Patel lifts it over mid off, not off the middle but hits it well enough to get it over that fielder. One taken.
On a length and on off, this is pushed to covers.
On the pads, this is clipped through mid-wicket for one.
Patel has looked quite solid since the time he has come out! Good length and on off, this is guided to point.
That is a sharp short ball, Patel is beaten for pace as he tries to pull. There is nice zip off the surface.
That is a good short ball, hurries Colin. He is late on the pull, it goes off the gloves and towards the leg side for one.
Fuller and on off, Patel now takes it on as he strokes it to wide mid off.
Shorter and on off, Colin pushes it towards covers and takes one.

Given out lbw! Ajaz Patel reviews. James Anderson darts in a full ball around off, shaping in off the seam at 82 mph. Ajaz Patel shows very limited footwork as he brings down a straight bat in defense. He misses and is pinged on the front pad. The appeal is made and the finger goes up. The DRS is in service and the UltraEdge detects an inside edge. Jimmy will have to wait for his fifer.
In the channel outside off, on a length and holding its line, Patel makes yet another watchful leave.
Dishes it out very full and wide outside off, inviting the drive, Patel lets it be.
Angles in a full ball, around off, Patel defends it by getting forward.
In the corridor of uncertainty, that is left alone for the keeper to collect.
Fullish and on middle, Colin de Grandhomme flicks it in front of square leg and rotates the strike. He is trusting Ajaz Patel here.
Nopes, double bluff. Broad puts it on a driving length outside off, Patel attempts to push it through the line but misses.
Square leg drops back. Short ball incoming?
On a length and outside off, angling in, Ajaz Patel leaves it alone.
FOUR! That's a good shot! Fuller in length and outside off, Patel reaches out for it and drills his drive through covers for a boundary. New Zealand move to 90!
In the channel outside off, on a good length, Patel shoulders arms.
Gets behind the line of the delivery and defends it solidly.
Pitches it up and around off, Patel pushes it down to mid on.
Around off, on a length, defended from the crease to the off side.
Ajaz Patel walks in next.

OUT! Southee holes out and his cameo is over! Clever bowling from James Anderson. He bangs it in short, around middle at 80 mph and it's well-directed. Tim Southee is taken by surprise, he takes his eyes off the ball as he swings his bat across the line. The top edge sends the ball flying to deep square leg where Matthew Potts is ready to pouch yet another skier. The 41-run stand is over and Anderson has four wickets.
Commentary.Howout: c Matthew Potts b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! This is good from Southee. Fuller in length, around middle, Southee finds it in the slot and heaves it over mid-wicket.

Slightly short again, around off, Southee flat-bats it down the ground through mid off. Stuart Broad gives the chase from mid on and slides near the fence to pull it back. Stokes has reached there too and he throws the ball back into play. Two runs taken.
Shortish and outside off, some extra energy on this delivery, Tim Southee pokes at it and misses.
Around off, on a length, this has been lifted behind the bowler for a couple of runs.

A touch short and on middle, Tim goes on his toes and helps it quietly to mid-wicket for a run. 39 runs in the entire morning session and now they have scored 39 more in the first 30 minutes or so of this session.
Back of a length, on top of off, Southee sticks back this time and tries to push inside the line but misses.
Wild swing and a miss! Broad is landing it a touch short and around off, Tim Southee clears his front leg for a big heave-ho but the ball swings away to beat his bat.
Shortish and on off, Southee drops his wrists and allows it through.
Beats the bat again! Stuart Broad delivers it around off, on a good length, Southee feels for it but gets beaten by the away movement.
Swing and a miss! Back of a length, outside off and shaping away, Southee rocks back to heave it across the line but misses.
Slightly short in length and outside off, Southee guides it down to third man for a run. The stand moves to 32 and NZ are 77 for 7.
Bouncer again, this time down the leg side, Tim ducks once more.
Digs it in short, around middle, Southee ducks.
FOUR! This is frustrating for England. Anderson loses his radar and slips a length ball down the leg side, Southee gets a fine tickle behind it and it scoots away to the fine leg fence.
FOUR! Just before this delivery, the deep point came in and Southee played it over him. Short in length and outside off, Tim Southee goes on his toes and whacks it over Ollie Pope.
Angles in a length ball around off, Colin de Grandhomme stays back and drops it down with gentle hands to covers. They steal a run.
Beauty from Broad. Serves it on a length and close to off again, the ball holds its line and beats the hanging defensive blade of Tim Southee.

Broad gets greedy and tries to repeat the last delivery from the leg stump line. It though goes down with the angle and beats the bat of Colin who tried to flick. It deflects off the pads to square leg and they cross for a leg bye.
Outswinger this time. It starts from around off, on a fuller length and then deviates away from the batter, Colin de Grandhomme offers no shot.
Bowls it on a good length and close to off, holding its line, Colin de Grandhomme takes his front leg forward to cover the line and then makes a leave.
Shortish and on off, played down towards covers for one.

FOUR! Vital runs, these! Short in length, around off and approaching the batter at a decent height. Southee rocks back and heaves it over mid-wicket for a boundary. Runs have come for New Zealand post Lunch but the damage is already done.
On a length and around off, Southee pushes it through point. The fielder there is in the deep and it's a single to close the over.

Another false shot but de Grandhomme survives. James Anderson angles it in on middle and leg, getting it to straighten a bit, Colin tries to flick but gets a big leading edge. It flies behind point, and then slows down as it approaches the fence. Three runs taken.
Lands it on a good length and around off, de Grandhomme is on the back foot as he pushes it to short cover.
A gentle delivery, on a length outside off and holding its line, Colin covers his stumps and shoulders arms.

Edged but safe! James Anderson hurls it across on a length and outside off, shaping away, Colin de Grandhomme pushes inside the line and edges it behind. It goes on the bounce to Zak Crawley at second slip.
Serves it on a good length around off, shaping back in, Tim goes on his toes and plays it down towards cover-point. They cross.
And again! Another outswinger, outside off, Colin de Grandhomme sees width and tries to force it through the line but misses.
Beaten! Moving away from the batter, around off, Colin de Grandhomme tries to drive but misses.
FOUR! Fine shot! Short in length, around off, Colin de Grandhomme camps back and plays a pull shot dominated by the bottom hand. It goes over mid-wicket and finds the fence.
Fuller and around off, Colin slices his attempted drive through cover-point for two.
50 up for New Zealand, at last. Angling in on middle, on a length, Southee works it through square leg for a run.
In the area outside off, Southee pushes at it and misses.
Stuart Broad it is who will bowl from the other end! Stokes could have gone for Matthew Potts but has gone for experience.
FOUR! Shot! Back of a length, around off, Colin de Grandhomme goes on the back foot and packs a punch through point. The outfield at Lord's is quick and it's a boundary for New Zealand.
Tim Southee walks out to bat! Will he swing at every ball too?

OUT! CAUGHT! Anderson doesn't shy away from digging it short again. He bangs it on middle at 84 mph, getting it high onto the batter, Kyle Jamieson is in top gear, and aims for another big shot across the line but this time it takes the top edge. Matthew Potts settles underneath it near the fence at deep backward square leg and takes the skier easily. Wicket number 3 for Jimmy and New Zealand are now 7 down with not even 50 on the board.
Commentary.Howout: c Matthew Potts b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Attack is the best form of defense. Anderson alters his length to go short, it's around off and in the hitting range for Jamieson. The tall man hangs on the back foot and powers it over mid-wicket.
On a length and around off, Kyle Jamieson looks to heave but ends up dragging it off the inner edge to mid-wicket.
Up and over! Anderson serves it on a length and outside off, Kyle tries for a lofted shot but slices it behind cover-point for two. The intention seems to be to attack.
Jimmy starts by delivering it slightly short and outside off, Kyle Jamieson plays at it late and taps it down in front of gully. The fielder there jumps and makes the stop.
We are back for the afternoon session! The England players make their way out to the middle. Colin de Grandhomme and Kyle Jamieson follow. James Anderson to begin. Here we go...
... DAY 1, SESSION 2 ...
Update - Matt Parkinson is set to make his long-awaited Test debut as he is named as the concussion substitute for Jack Leach.

New Zealand will be disappointed. Despite it being a great strip to bat on, the initial phase was always going to be tough. Their openers didn't show the right application, and there were many avoidable shots. The tourists have their backs to the wall now and need someone to play a marathon knock to bail them out. Can they survive the afternoon session? Do join us at 6.10 pm IST (12.40 pm GMT) to find out.

Exceptional morning session for England! It was supposed to be a batting day at Lord's, both captains showed the willingness to bat first, but the way things have panned out, the hosts will be happy that Ben Stokes lost the toss. James Anderson and Stuart Broad were reunited to use the new ball, and they showed exemplary control over their line and length. The pitch offered just enough juice, and the awesome twosome dictated terms. The newbie, Matthew Potts, also proved his mettle and looks ripe for this format already. He extended the good work and claimed three wickets in his first spell of Test cricket.

Takes one on the body! Shorter one around off, Colin de Grandhomme stands back, he does not take on the short ball but is too late in moving out of the way. Gets hit on the body. That will be Lunch on Day 1.
Back of the length and on off, Colin de Grandhomme pulls this one through mid-wicket for a brace.
On a good length and outside off, this is left alone towards Ben Foakes.

An appeal for LBW but turned down! Stokes asks if there is an inside edge and Potts does not feel so. It is reviewed. Time for the replays! NOT OUT! UltraEdge shows a spike and there is an inside edge! Really difficult to judge though if it was bat first or pad first as it looked very close. Length and outside off, this lands and jags back in. Colin de Grandhomme looks to defend but he seems to have missed it and it hits the pad. An appeal but turned down. It is reviewed but England lose one.
On a good length and outside leg, slower too, Colin de Grandhomme leaves it alone.
Length delivery on middle, this is defended towards the mid on region.

The game pauses for a while! The crowd is on its feet, clapping and celebrating the legend of the game Shane Warne. We lost the magical spinner a few months back. The man with jersey number 23 gets applause for 23 seconds. Rest in peace, Warnie.
Back of the length and on middle, Kyle Jamieson jumps a bit and blocks it away.
Length delivery on off, Kyle Jamieson looks to flick it but gets an inside edge as the ball rolls towards mid-wicket.
Length delivery and outside off, this is guided towards point.
Touch full and outside off, Kyle Jamieson lets it go.
Length and outside leg, Kyle Jamieson tries to flick it but misses.
On middle, this is clipped towards square leg for one.
On a length and outside off, Kyle Jamieson punches it towards covers.
Kyle Jamieson is the new batter.

OUT! BOWLED! Matthew Potts gets another one! An error of judgment costs Tom Blundell! He did leave a few which went close past the off pole but this was a poor leave, to be honest. Matthew Potts goes fuller, fuller than a length that is and gets it back in from just around off. That is not a ball you leave but Tom Blundell does so. It slams into the off pole. England are into the bowling all-rounders now. Tom Blundell was usually leaving the balls on length but this one was a little too full. Clever stuff from Potts. Can England get another one before Lunch?
Commentary.Howout: b Matthew Potts

Commentary.Commentary: Similar to the last delivery, Tom Blundell again leaves it towards the keeper.
On a length and outside off, Tom Blundell leaves it through towards Ben Foakes.
Sticks to his length and bowls it outside off, Tom Blundell guides it to point.
Good length and outside off, Tom Blundell lets it go.
On a length and outside off, this is left alone towards the keeper.
Good-length delivery and on middle, Colin de Grandhomme looks to flick it but misses and gets hit on the thigh pad, the ball rolls towards the slip cordon.
Length ball outside off swinging it in, Colin de Grandhomme shoulders arms and leaves it through to the keeper.
On a good length and outside off, this is left alone towards the keeper.
Back of a length and on off, Colin de Grandhomme leaves it alone.
On a length and on leg, Colin de Grandhomme looks to flick it but misses and the ball hits his pads.
James Anderson (6-5-4-2) returns for his second spell.
Touch full and outside off, Tom Blundell looks to drive it but gets an inside edge as the ball races towards short mid-wicket.
On middle, this is defended out solidly.
Length ball on leg, quicker too, Tom Blundell tries to block it but gets an inside edge as the ball rolls towards short leg.
Good length and outside off, Tom Blundell shoulders arms on this one.

A huge appeal and the finger is raised! Tom Blundell reviews! NOT OUT! UltraEdge shows an INSIDE EDGE! That is the reason why Tom Blundell reviewed it almost immediately. This is on length, it comes back in from outside off. Tom Blundell puts in a good stride forward and tries to defend. There are two sounds and one of them is coming from the pad. An appeal and the finger is raised. Blundell reviews and the replays show that the on-field call has to be overturned. The New Zealand dressing room will breathe a huge sigh of relief.
On a length and outside off, Tom Blundell tries to block it but misses.
Another leave as this is yet again bowled outside off. Not played at.
That goes over the off pole. Left on length. On off, Colin de Grandhomme shoulders arms to it.
Now follows the two boundaries with one! Good batting! On a length and around off, this is guided towards point for one.
FOUR! Full face of the bat! That is a wonderful stroke! Fuller and on middle, this is timed past mid on and it races away to the fence.
EDGY FOUR! Almost another wicket! Fuller and on off, Tom Blundell, with hardly any foot movement, pushes at it, this goes off the inside edge past the leg pole and down to the fine leg fence.
Outside off, left alone.
A very confident looking drive to begin with! Fuller and on off, Colin de Grandhomme pushes it to mid off. End of another successful over for England.
Colin de Grandhomme walks in next. He is known for his aggressive style of batting and it will be interesting to watch his approach.

OUT! TIMBER! Plays it on and Matthew Potts has another one, and England have five in the first session. Just as a stand was looking to build, England have struck! This one probably skids through. Back of a length and on middle, this zips through. Daryl Mitchell goes back and looks to defend but is a touch late into the shot. It hits the under-edge and then goes onto the stumps.
Commentary.Howout: b Matthew Potts

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! That is a really good shot! Good timing and finds the gap too. Should release a little bit of pressure. Short and on the body, Daryl Mitchell swivels and pulls it through backward square leg. There are a couple of fielders in the deep but it beats both and goes into the fence.
Angled into the pads, Tom Blundell looks to flick but misses. It hits the pad and rolls on the leg side. A leg bye is taken.
Good length and on off, Tom Blundell guides it to point.
Back of a length and outside off, left alone.

BREAKING - Jack Leach is showing signs of concussion, so as per the protocol, Leach has been withdrawn from this Test match. No word on his replacement yet. Wishing Leach a speedy recovery. We will keep you posted in case of any new development.
Good leave yet again! Outside off, Daryl Mitchell shoulders arms to this one. Another tidy over and England continue to pile on the pressure.
When runs are hard to come by, such quick runs are gold! On middle, Blundell works it towards mid on and gets to the other end.
On the fuller side and on middle, Tom Blundell pushes it to mid on.
Outside off, not played at.

Another good leave! Yet another one on a length and outside off, Tom lets it go with a good stride forward. Broad does get the ball back in nicely and we have seen him dismiss batters when they try leaving it. He is threatening here.
A good leave in the end! This is on a length, well outside off, this one comes back in a long way. Tom Blundell puts in a good stride forward and leaves it alone. A good leave in the end.
Outside off, not played at. Another testing over from Potts comes to an end.
Solid! Length and on off, defended. Giving nothing away at the moment are the English bowlers.

Now the one that goes away! Outstanding stuff! Length and on off, this lands and moves away. Mitchell looks to defend but is beaten all ends up. This is quality stuff. Taking the ball away and bringing it back in from the same spot. He has really impressed so far.
This one comes back in sharply! This lands on a length and outside off, jags back in. Mitchell misses as he tries to defend and gets hit high on the pad.
Angled into the pads again, from wide of the crease, this is worked down to fine leg for one.
Angled into the middle pole, Tom Blundell works it to mid-wicket. The movement which was there earlier on is not as extravagant as it was. Batting is getting easier as expected.
On a good length and on middle, this is blocked back towards Stuart Broad.
FOUR! Fuller and in the line of the stumps, at 85 mph, this is flicked through the mid-wicket region for a boundary.
Fuller one this time and on middle, Daryl Mitchell tries to block it but gets an outside edge. The ball falls short towards the fielder at fourth slip.
Length delivery on off, Daryl Mitchell defends it towards mid on.
On a good length and on leg, quicker too, Tom Blundell tries to flick it but misses. It goes off his pads to square leg and they collect a leg bye.
On a good length and outside off, Tom Blundell shoulders arms and leaves it through to the keeper.
Maiden over from Matthew Potts. Length delivery on off, this is again defended towards the mid on region.
Length delivery on middle, this is eased towards the mid on region.
Sticks to his length and delivers it around middle, this is defended back towards Matthew Potts.
Length ball outside off, Daryl Mitchell leaves it alone towards the keeper.
On a good length and outside off, this is driven straight towards the fielder at short cover.
On a good length and on off, this is pushed back towards the bowler.
Good length delivery on middle, this is eased towards mid on.
On a length and outside leg, Tom Blundell tries to give it a fine tickle but misses. The keeper collects it diving to his left.
Sticks to his length and on middle, Tom Blundell flicks it past square leg for a brace.
On a good length and on middle, this is eased towards the mid on region.
Length ball on off, Tom Blundell tries to block it but gets an inside edge as the ball rolls towards short leg.
On a good length and on middle, this is defended back towards Stuart Broad.
A length ball outside off, Daryl Mitchell tries to block it but misses. Loud appeal from Ben Foakes but the finger stays down.
Good length ball down the middle and leg line, Tom Blundell flicks it towards square leg for one.
Sticks to his line and length, Tom Blundell tries to block it but misses.
On a good length and outside off, this is again left alone through to the keeper.
Back of the length and outside off, Tom Blundell gets in two minds but leaves it alone in the end.
A length ball outside off, Tom Blundell defends it towards gully.

DRINKS! England and Stokes just could not have asked for a better start! They are all over the Kiwis at the moment. 4 wickets in the first hour and they have given away just the 12 runs. All the three bowlers to bowl have been excellent and have made brilliant use of the condition. New Zealand, on the other hand, need a partnership. They really need to enter Lunch without losing another wicket. Easier said than done but the Kiwis will have to do so.
Streaky! Fuller in length and around middle, Daryl Mitchell tries driving but it takes the outside edge. Doesn't carry to gully. Fifth maiden for Jimmy!

Sliding down the leg side, on a length, Daryl Mitchell doesn't get enough bat behind his attempted flick shot. It takes his thigh pad and rolls behind. Foakes is quick to get to the ball, to his left.
On a length and outside off, the batter leaves it again and the ball dives on its way to the keeper.
Serves it on a length again, outside off, Mitchell guards his stumps and allows it through.
Angles in a length ball on off, Daryl Mitchell is on the back foot as he defends it to the off side.
A gentle outswinger, in the zone outside off, Daryl lets it through to the keeper.
Delivers it on a good length and outside off, Tom Blundell allows it through to the keeper. Brilliant first over from Matthew Potts, a wicket maiden.
Tom Blundell walks out to bat!

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! What a debut wicket for Matthew Potts! He is running in celebration after bowling just five balls in his Test career. Kane Williamson exits and New Zealand are in tatters. It's a scrambled seam delivery, fuller and around off, at 85 kph, Williamson decides to defend the line with soft hands but it's not soft enough. The outside edge flies to the right of Ben Foakes who completes a great catch.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Foakes b Matthew Potts

Commentary.Commentary: Fuller and outside off, seaming away, Williamson pushes at it and misses.
On off,  a length ball, defended.
Lands it on a length, around off, angling in, Kane defends it from the back foot.
Begins well with a delivery in the channel outside off, getting it to move away, Kane shoulders arms.

It is time for the debutant to come on! Matthew Potts gets the ball in hand. What a moment for him. A debut at Lord's and the first ball he will be bowling to is Kane Williamson, one of the modern greats.
Fuller in length and outside off, nipping away a bit, Daryl Mitchell leaves it alone.
Back of a length, close to off and angling in, Daryl Mitchell goes on the back foot and defends it on the leg side.
Bouncer outside off, at 82 mph, Daryl Mitchell ducks.
Around off, on a length and angling in, Daryl Mitchell gets forward and defends it to the off side.
FOUR! First boundary of the Test match and also the first runs off James Anderson. Fuller and on middle, Daryl Mitchell leans across and flicks it through mid-wicket for a boundary.
In the zone outside off, left alone.
Again the length is full, around off, Daryl Mitchell loses his balance a bit as he pushes it out towards covers. It rolls in the gap and he picks up a single.
Fuller and around off, defended off the front foot to the off side.
Beaten! On a length and around off, moving away, Daryl Mitchell pokes and misses.

Shout for a caught behind! The finger has stayed down. Back of a length, around off and angling in, Daryl Mitchell tries to defend the line but it straightens a hint to beat the bat. There is some sound as it goes to Ben Foakes, they appeal but the umpire stays unmoved. Stokes decides not to review it. That sounded more fabric than wood. The replays show that it clipped Mitchell's pocket.
Slightly short and on off, Daryl Mitchell goes on the back foot and plays it down to point.

OUT! CAUGHT! Jonny is in business again at third slip and the legendary bowling pair of Board and Anderson have combined to pick three wickets. Normalcy resumes for the Three Lions! This delivery is hurled on a length and outside off, at 84 mph, Devon Conway gets on the front foot to defend but ends up pushing inside the line with firm hands. It flies towards Jonny Bairstow who snaps a lovely low catch, inches above the ground. New Zealand are in big trouble now!
Commentary.Howout: c Jonny Bairstow b Stuart Broad

Commentary.Commentary: Lands it on a length outside off, Kane Williamson initially looks to put his bat inside the line but then pulls out. Fourth maiden in a row for James Anderson, he is yet to concede a run.
Identical to the last delivery, this time the length is a tad fuller, Kane lets it go and carefully keeps his gloves away from the trajectory of the ball.
Big inswinger from Jimmy! He shortens his length slightly and delivers it outside off, Kane sways away.

JUST SHORT! Williamson's soft hands save him. Fuller and angling in around off at 82 mph, Kane Williamson tries to defend the line but it nips away a bit to take a soft outside edge. It drops in front of first slip as Ben Foakes dives across.
In the channel outside off, landing on a good length and shaping away, Kane Williamson lets it through to the keeper.
Angling in, on a length around off, Kane Williamson allows the ball to come to him and taps it down to gully.
Fullish and on off, Devon Conway takes his front leg forward and pushes it defensively to covers.
Nearly! Broad steams in from 'round the wicket and lands it on a length outside off. Devon Conway hangs his bat out to dry and it beats the outside edge by a whisker.
Pitches it up and close to off, Kane Williamson presses forward and plays it with soft hands towards cover-point. They steal a quick run.
Fuller and on off, angling in, Williamson defends it off his front foot.

Halt in play! Leach is in pain after he tried stopping the ball with a dive. The physio is out. This does not look good though. Jack Leach is going off for now and Harry Brook is on the field as his substitute.

Jack Leach in trouble! Fuller in length and outside off, Conway commits himself to the drive and slices it off the outside half of his blade. It races behind through gully and Leach chases it down. He pulls it back in but then falls awkwardly, with his head hitting the ground hard. Jack Leach has stayed down, in pain. The physio has come out and there are a few concerned faces around. Meanwhile, three runs have been added to the scoreboard.
Fractionally short and angling down the leg side, Kane nudges it down to fine leg and opens his account with a single.
Bowls it on a good length and outside off, Devon Conway shoulders arms. Yet another wicket maiden for Jimmy!
Fuller and on off, angling in, Devon defends it ahead of his front pad.
In the channel outside off, left alone.
Devon Conway walks out to bat! He had a really good time in England and he needs a good knock here.

OUT! CAUGHT! Jonny Bairstow is in action again, this time he dropped it in the first attempt but then takes it on the rebound. Back of a length this time, around off at 81 mph, Tom Latham goes on the back foot to punch it through the line but gets a big fat outside edge. The ball flies towards third slip where Jonny Bairstow tries to catch it with both hands but it slips out. The ball hits his wrists and then chest before lobbing in front of him. Jonny keeps his eyes on it, puts in a dive immediately and catches it with his right hand, diving forward. The English players are delighted. New Zealand have both their openers back in the hut.
Commentary.Howout: c Jonny Bairstow b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: This one is very wide outside off, fuller in length and leaving the batter with the away movement, Latham has nothing to offer.
Anderson continues with his 'round the wicket angle for the left-hander. Serves it on a length around off, getting it to shape away, Latham makes a watchful leave.
This one is angled in around off, fuller in length, Williamson defends it gently to short mid-wicket. Good pressure bowling from England.
Fuller in length and outside off, Williamson keeps his bat close to his front pad and allows it through. The ball moves quite a bit after going past the Kiwi skipper.
Serves it on a good length and wide outside off, Williamson shoulders arms.

Tom opens his account now! Fuller in length around off, Latham uses the angle of the bowler and nudges it towards mid-wicket. He scampers across for a single and completes it with ease as the fielder scores a direct hit at the bowler's end.
A gentle delivery this time, full and outside off, Tom lets it be.
Slightly short in length, around off and angling in with some extra bounce, Latham is hurried up and misses the ball. It deflects off his thigh pad to the off side.
Around off, on a length, Williamson tries to defend but it straightens a bit to beat the bat. The ball strikes him on the thigh pad. End of a fine over, a wicket maiden!
Anderson again gets it to shape away from the batter, outside off, Kane has nothing to do with it.
Outside off, left alone.
A big inswinger from Anderson, it lands on a length outside off, and curls back in, Kane keeps his bat close to his body, leans back a touch and makes way for the ball.
In the zone outside off, moving away, Williamson allows it through.

Kane Williamson walks out to bat now! The skipper was not in the best of forms in the recently concluded Indian T20 League but he can take a lot more time for himself as this format allows that but he faces a tough challenge as the ball is doing a bit. Four slips and a gully waiting...

OUT! CAUGHT! James Anderson strikes in his second over. This is a superb one-handed catch by Jonny Bairstow. England have had issues with their slip catching but this one will make them feel confident. It's a length delivery in the channel outside off, shaping away a tad at 81 mph, Will Young could have left this alone but has a needless poke at it with unsure footwork. The ball takes a soft outside edge and flies towards third slip. It appears to be dying down but Jonny goes down, stretches his left hand out and it sticks. England are ecstatic!
Commentary.Howout: c Jonny Bairstow b James Anderson

Commentary.Commentary: Beautiful delivery! Broad hurls across a full delivery, close to off and straightening just a touch, Latham has a nervous poke inside the line and misses.
On a length and outside off, angling in a bit, Tom covers his stumps and allows it through.
Good stop at gully! Broad lands it on a length and outside off, Latham pushes at it and it goes off the outer half. The gully fielder dives across to his left to stop the ball.
Goes very full and around off, as a surprise delivery, Latham brings a straight bat down and pushes it back towards the bowler.
Broad also switches to 'round the wicket for the southpaw. He serves it on a length and in the region outside off, Latham leaves it alone.
New Zealand are underway! Broad begins his spell with an inswinger. It's on a length and around off, Young plays with soft hands towards square leg and opens his account with a single.
Who will bowl from the other end then? Stuart Broad it is. Three slips and a gully in place.
A gentle outswinger, quite wide outside off, an easy leave for Latham. Jimmy begins with a maiden.
In the channel outside off, on a good length, this time Tom confidently covers the line and shoulders arms.
Back of a length, around off and angling in, Latham plays late near his body and taps it down towards gully.
Beauty of a delivery! The 'round the wicket angle is certainly troubling the batter. It's on and around off, on a length and straightening off the seam, Latham plays inside the line and gets beaten.
Anderson goes closer to the off stump line, the length is slightly fuller and it holds its line, Latham makes a watchful leave.
James Anderson begins with an outswinger. He lands it on a length and close to off, Latham feels for it inside the line as the ball beats the bat.

We are moments away from the first ball then! England are in a huddle and now walk out to the middle. They are followed by Will Young and Tom Latham! It is partly sunny and there is also a big cloud hovering above the ground. It will be interesting to see if there will be some movement for the bowler and if there is, the great man, James Anderson will surely get it. He is the one opening the bowling for the hosts. Here we go...

Ben Stokes, the English skipper, says that they would have batted as well. Regarding him leading the team, Stokes replies that it's not too different, it's just that he will have to make a few more decisions. Informs about Matthew Potts' debut and praises his skills. Informs about the illness of Graham Thorpe who is in hospital at the moment and he is wearing his name on his jersey to show support.

Kane Williamson, the captain of New Zealand, says that they want to bat first as the sun is out and it looks like a good surface. Mentions that he is happy to be back in the side and informs that Ajaz Patel along with Tim Southee, Trent Boult, Kyle Jamieson and Colin de Grandhomme constitute their bowling attack. Shares that they have prepared well and are looking forward to this game.
NEW ZEALAND (PLAYING XI) - Tom Latham, Will Young, Kane Williamson (C), Devon Conway, Daryl Mitchell, Tom Blundell (WK), Colin de Grandhomme, Kyle Jamieson, Tim Southee, Ajaz Patel, Trent Boult.
ENGLAND (PLAYING XI) - Zak Crawley, Alex Lees, Ollie Pope, Joe Root, Jonny Bairstow, Ben Stokes (C), Ben Foakes (WK), Matthew Potts, Jack Leach, Stuart Broad, James Anderson.
TOSS - New Zealand HAVE WON THE TOSS AND ELECTED TO BAT!

The hosts have already announced their XI! They have included a spinner in it and also, they have turned to the experienced heads of Anderson and Broad. Both missed the series against the Windies and they are now back into the mix. They have a debutant too as Matthew Potts will be featuring for his country for the very first time whereas the batting is more or less similar to the one that played in the West Indies. As far as the Kiwis are concerned, Trent Boult could be in line to play this Test despite arriving last Monday. Also, they have to make a decision on playing a spinner for this match. Ajaz Patel could feature for the first time after his heroic 10-wicket haul in an innings against India. Stay tuned, toss is not far away now.

It is a beginning of a new era for England! They have a new coach who is a Kiwi himself, Brendon McCullum and also, a new captain Stokes. It will be great to see how things pan out under the two for the hosts. One thing is for sure though, we will witness some exciting and aggressive cricket from the Three Lions. The Kiwis, on the other hand, haven't won a Test series this year despite playing two at home. They drew against both, South Africa and Bangladesh. The tourists though have happy memories of facing England as they beat them the last time they visited this part of the world. Can they do it again? We will find out.

After almost two months of fast, exciting T20 cricket, it is now time for the oldest and the longest format of the game to take the centre stage. England and New Zealand will lock horns in a three-match Test series with the first one being played at Lord's. Welcome to the coverage and stay with us for all the updates.
... MATCH DAY ...
We are back! The Kiwi openers, Will Young and Tom Latham make their way out to the middle. James Anderson will start with the new ball. Here we go...

Have to say, New Zealand have a slight advantage at the moment! England are going to bat last and if New Zealand can bat well, they will have the hosts under massive pressure. On the other hand, the hosts will hope their bowlers can do something similar to what they did in the first innings. Will the bowlers continue to dominate or will the batters have their say this time? Stick around to find out.

England, on the other hand, will be very disappointed. Their top three played decently to get them into a good position but the middle order and the lower order showed no fight. 8 of their batters did not pass the 10-run mark and that saw England take only a slender lead.

End of an excellent bowling performance from the Kiwis and courtesy of their bowlers, from being down and out in the game, the visitors are right back into this one. Who would have thought at 92-2 England would not end up with a big lead! Well from there on, it all went downhill for them. They have lost 8 wickets for just 49 runs and all the credit goes to Southee and Boult. Especially the former who was the pick and he got able support from the others.

OUT! CAUGHT AT SLIPS! Trent Boult angles across a length ball, around off and leaving the batter, Matt Parkinson has a firm push inside the line but only to edge it towards first slip. Another safe catch is taken by Daryl Mitchell. England are all out for 141, gaining a lead of 9 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Daryl Mitchell b Trent Boult

Commentary.Commentary: Full and around off, angling in, Anderson clips it behind square leg for a single.
Steep bounce this time, around off, Anderson fends it off awkwardly to point.
Walks forward with the pull shot but again drags it off the inner edge to mid-wicket.
On a length and around off, Anderson is on the back foot as he blocks.
Fuller again, around middle and leg, this time Matt plays a mistimed on-drive but gets two. Lead is 8.
FOUR! Fine shot! Too full and around middle, Matt Parkinson shows the full face of the bat and caresses it down to long on for a boundary.
Around off, angling in on a fuller length, Matt drives it down to mid off.
Beaten! That's a beauty from wide of the crease. Outswinger, close to off, Matt Parkinson plays the line and is beaten by the away movement.
First Test runs for Matt Parkinson and he takes England into the lead. Southee gets a length ball to angle in around middle, Matt eases it in front of square leg for two.
Bouncer and around off, Matt Parkinson ducks underneath it.
SCORES LEVEL! Fullish and around off, Anderson drives it down the ground through mid off and collects a couple of runs.

Shout for an lbw! Not given. Williamson is not interested in reviewing it. A toe-crusher from Boult, around leg at 86 mph, Anderson fails to dig it out. The appeal is not entertained as it's heading down the leg side.
Fullish and around off, Anderson stays back to defend but gets beaten as the ball curves away after landing.
Ho! Ho! Ho! Anderson tries to switch into the hitting mode. Steps back, makes room and attempts for a big heave across the line. Only manages to drag it off the inner half to mid on.
Delivers it on a length and outside off, Jimmy again pushes at it and misses.
Back of a length, around off, Anderson feels for it and gets beaten.
On a length around off, angling in, Matt Parkinson defends it by getting forward.

The last man, the concussion substitute for Jack Leach and someone making his debut, Matt Parkinson walks out to the middle. A huge round of applause as he walks out. He is also the first-ever concussion substitute for England.

OUT! CAUGHT! Brilliant from Southee. He goes wide of the crease and delivers a length ball outside off. It's angling in and then straightens after pitching at 82 mph. Foakes could have left it alone but ends up flirting inside the line. It takes a thick outside edge and Daryl Mitchell takes a simple catch at first slip. Tim nears yet another fifer at Lord's. The deficit is 2 runs, wicket left for England is one as the last recognized batter departs.
Commentary.Howout: c Daryl Mitchell b Tim Southee

Commentary.Commentary: In the channel outside off, an outswinger, Foakes lets it be.
Delivers it on a good length, and just outside off, Foakes stays back and plays it down defensively to covers.
Angling down the leg side, it's nudged behind square leg for one.
Southee bangs it in short, around off, the pitch doesn't offer much pace and Anderson goes on the back foot to guide it through backward point. Two runs.
Pitches it up and around off, Anderson pushes it in the gap at covers and keeps strike with a run. The deficit is 5 now.
Rising onto the batter, from a shortish length around off, Anderson is on the back foot as he defends it down to short leg once more.
Boult alters his length to go fuller, around off, Anderson defends it by closing the face of his bat, again towards short leg.
Back of a length, on off and angling in, Anderson goes on his toes and jams it down in front of short leg.
Foakes uses the angle of the bowler and works it through square leg. Ben takes a single and is trusting Anderson here to survive four balls.
Boult comes from 'round the wicket and angles in a shortish ball on off, Foakes gets across and helps it down to mid-wicket.
Anderson survives the three balls he had to! A wicket and a boundary in the over. Length and outside off, left alone.
Good length and on off, Anderson pushes it to covers.

EDGED BUT SHORT! Good by Southee! There was a leg slip, a short leg and hence, Anderson might have been expecting a short ball. Southee goes slightly fuller and outside off. Anderson has a poke at it with no foot movement. He gets an outside edge which lands short of the second slip fielder.
James Anderson walks out to bat now! It will be interesting to see his approach.

OUT! TIMBER! The leg stump has been uprooted and Southee gets his revenge! One shot too many there from Broad. Southee bowls this behind a driving length. This time he starts on off and then gets it to shape back in. Broad swings but misses by a long way and the leg stump goes for a walk. England still trail by 7, the Kiwis need two more wickets.
Commentary.Howout: b Tim Southee

Commentary.Commentary: Swing and a miss! Drags his length ball, gets this one to shape back in from outside off. Broad swings but misses.

FOUR! It is up there and Broad goes after it. Not a bad idea to play this way. We saw the New Zealand lower order score some handy runs like this and all of these runs will also be vital for England. Fuller and on middle, Broad thumps it down the ground to the mid on fence. He also has a glance at Southee as he runs towards the other end.
Tim Southee to bowl from the other end!
Yet another leave to end the first over of the day! A good one for the hosts! Outside off, on the fuller side. Not played at.
Makes the batter play this time! A back-of-a-length ball on off, defended.
Yet again a fuller one, just outside off, Foakes does not play at it.
Fuller and outside off, Foakes shoulders arms to this one.
First run off the bat today! Length and on off, Broad guides it towards point for one. England only trail by 11 now.

FOUR BYES! Bonus runs for England. They won't mind how they come as long as they do. Not the start Boult or the Kiwis would have wanted. This is short but down the leg side. Keeps going away with the angle. Broad evades it, the keeper has no chance and it goes down to the fine leg fence.

It is time for the action to begin! The New Zealand players are out in the middle and now the English batters, Stuart Broad and Ben Foakes walk out to continue their innings. Trent Boult will start the proceedings. Here we go...

After the first two sessions, England gained control of this Test match, but their batting crumbled late in the day to send all the good work of their bowlers down the drain. It's all about starting fresh on a new day with both teams on a level playing field. Who will blink first on Friday? Stay tuned to find out...

Welcome back, folks! It's great to have your company again. Day 1 of the Lord's Test got dominated by the bowlers from both teams, can the batters find their voice on Day 2? This venue is known to dish out excellent batting decks, and to be honest, there are no demons in it. 17 wickets in a day's play was a surprise, and had we not lost 12 overs due to the slow over-rate, we could have New Zealand batting again for the second time on the first day itself. Let's see what's in store this morning.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1 ...

Right then, this Test match has moved along at a brisk pace but it is still hanging in the balance. England have a deficit of 16 runs with three wickets in the kitty. They will hope for their tail to wag and hand them a lead of at least 50 runs, if not more. On the contrary, New Zealand's aim will be to pick the remaining wickets quickly and bat better in the second essay. Day 2 is going to be the moving day after such a breezy start to this Test match and the first ball will be at 3.30 pm IST (10 am GMT). Do join us early for the build-up and until then, take care and goodbye!

It was turning out to be a day to forget for the touring team after the English openers got off to a steady start. But once they picked up a couple of wickets, we saw them getting their rhythm with the ball. The wicket of Joe Root opened the floodgates for the Black Caps and they went on to reduce England from 92 for 2 to 100 for 7. A familiar collapse for the home team these days as they surrendered the advantage. All the Kiwi bowlers delivered with great aplomb and worked hard on their accuracy.

As already mentioned, it was a bowlers' day out at Lord's. At the start, James Anderson and Stuart Broad provided England with a perfectly accurate start and picked wickets as well to push the Kiwis on the back foot. The debutant Matthew Potts joined the party as a first change bowler, and he also left a telling impact. Potts and Jimmy combined for eight wickets and restricted New Zealand to a below-par total in the first innings.

The summer of English cricket is back and it's back with a bang! 17 wickets on the first day, and the bowlers had a ball. We fell short by 12 overs, but the action we got was full of entertainment. The players are leaving the field, and the Kiwi players are all smiles. They pulled things back superbly in the last session and have earned that smile.
Bowls it full and lands it close to off, Broad brings his bat down to defend but it takes the inner edge and runs down to fine leg. A single is taken and that will be it. Stumps on Day 1!
Back of a length, outside off, Foakes punches it through covers and picks up another three in this over.
Delivers it full and around off, Ben defends it to the off side.
Ben Foakes picks up the bouncer slightly late and ducks awkwardly.
Fine shot! Full and wide outside off, Broad opens the face of his bat as he reaches out for it and steers it through point for another three runs.
Fuller and on off, Foakes slices his attempted drive and it races away through backward point. The fielder pulls it back just before the fence and saves one.
Fuller in length and outside off, Broad tries driving but without any footwork and gets beaten.
Boult mixes it up. Delivers an outswinger this time, around off, Broad pushes inside the line and misses.
Appeal for an lbw, nothing doing. Inswinger from Boult but it starts from the middle stump line and goes down. Broad is on the back foot and is thudded on the pads.
Around off, on a shortish length, Broad leaps as he pushes at it and misses.
Sliding down the leg side, Broad fails to flick and it goes off his pads to fine leg. Kyle Jamieson makes a fine stop near the fence. Two leg byes.
FOUR BYES! Boult bangs in a bouncer, around leg, it flies over the front shoulder of Broad and beats Tom Blundell as well. Bonus boundary for England.
Very full and around off, pushed out to covers.
And again. Another outswinger goes past the hanging blade of Ben Foakes.
Southee gets his outswinger to land near the off stump line, Foakes feels for it and gets beaten.
Delivers it on a length and outside off, Foakes drives but finds the cover fielder.
Angling in around off, on a length, Ben defends it.
Outside off, left alone.
Spears it in, very full and on middle, Broad keeps it out safely to the off side. Splending over!
Stuart Broad is in next.

OUT! CAUGHT! Just two balls and Potts returns. What a dramatic turnaround - 5 wickets for 8 runs. Trent Boult digs it in short, around middle and surprises the batter. Matthew Potts takes his eyes off the ball as he attempts to fend it away. But the ball takes the gloves and lobs behind to Daryl Mitchell at first slip. Matthew Potts doesn't wait for the finger to go up and starts his journey back to the pavilion. England still trail by 32 runs and have just 3 wickets left.
Commentary.Howout: c Daryl Mitchell b Trent Boult

Commentary.Commentary: Serves it on a good length around middle, Potts defends it to the leg side.
Debutant Matthew Potts walks in next to bat. Four wickets with the ball, can he contribute with the bat as well?

OUT! DRAGS IT ON! Wickets are tumbling here and the game is turning. Boult delivered a couple of inswingers and then serves a shortish delivery outside off which goes on with the angle at 79 mph. Bairstow hangs on the back foot as he chases the ball but only to drag it onto the stumps via a thick inside edge. New Zealand are roaring at Lord's!
Commentary.Howout: b Trent Boult

Commentary.Commentary: Movement again. On a length around off, shaping in and beating Bairstow's bat. Strikes him high on the back leg.
Back of a length, around off and nipping back in, Jonny stays back to cut but it beats the inside edge. Blundell fails to collect and they take two byes. 100 up!
Trent Boult returns for another burst. Kane Williamson going for the kill.
Fuller on middle, defended on the leg side. A wicket maiden for Southee.

Huge shout for a caught behind! The finger stays down. Back of a length and angling down the leg side, Foakes tries to glance but misses. There is some noise as Blundell collects it to his left and they appeal. Nothing from the umpire and the Kiwis decide not to review.
Fuller in length, on middle, Foakes defends it.
Ben Foakes arrives.

OUT! CAUGHT! What a phase of play for the Black Caps. They have now hunted down five wickets. This day has taken a twist, it was all England in the first two sessions but suddenly in the last session, the tourists have got their rhythm. 3 wickets for 6 runs in the last 20 balls! Southee delivers it on a length and around off at 84 mph, Ben Stokes stands back to punch it down the ground but gets an outside edge behind. Tom Blundell takes yet another catch and the English skipper has an early exit. Deficit - 34 runs.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Blundell b Tim Southee

Commentary.Commentary: That is left alone for the keeper to collect.
In the zone outside off, left alone.
Around off, Stokes walks across and works it through square leg for one.
Lovely delivery! Colin de Grandhomme serves it a bit short and around off, it nips away lately. Stokes is squared up in defense and it goes off his thigh pad to the slip region.
Colin gets the ball to bend back into the batter this time. Around off, Ben walks across again and defends it close to his body.
That's a curler. Landing on a length and outside off, moving away off the seam, Stokes shuffles across the stumps and then leaves it alone.
Fuller and around off, Jonny Bairstow drives it down the ground, to the right of mid off, and takes a single.
Wide outside off, shaping away, Jonny leaves.
This is an inswinger. Landing on a length and outside off, Stokes covers the stumps and shoulders arms.
Bowls it in the channel outside off, Stokes leaves.
Ben Stokes, the skipper walks out to bat. He has not put a foot wrong in the game so far, can he do well with the bat?

OUT! GIVEN LBW! The ploy to stand across the stumps in his stance has brought the downfall of Alex Lees.​ Tim Southee speeds in and hurls across a length ball around middle and leg, at 83 mph, Lees tries to flick but misses. He is rapped on the pads, they appeal and the finger goes up. Alex Lees has a word with his partner and takes the DRS. The UltraEdge confirms that there is no bat and the Ball Tracking shows two reds and a yellow. Umpire's call and Alex is back in the pavilion. England have now lost four wickets and the advantage they gained is slipping away. The deficit is 36 runs.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Tim Southee

Commentary.Commentary: A near yorker around off, Lees brings his bat down and gets it away off the bottom edge, back towards the bowler.
Inswinger this time, on a length and outside off, Lees covers his stumps and shoulders arms.
Southee angles in a length ball, from around off, Alex walks across and helps it to mid-wicket.
Outside off, left alone. End of a successful over for de Grandhomme.

FOUR LEG BYES! Colin de Grandhomme looks for a delivery pitching on middle and leg, and straightens. But he slips it down the leg side, Bairstow fails to flick but it takes his pads and races away to fine leg.
On a driving length outside off, Jonny takes a stride forward and then makes a leave.
Hurls across a good-length delivery, in the zone outside off, Jonny Bairstow allows it through to the keeper.
Jonny Bairstow makes his way down the stairs which means he is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! That's a sharp catch to dismiss Joe Root. It appears to be an effort ball from Colin de Grandhomme. He bends his back to deliver it short and outside off, at 76 mph, Joe Root transfers his weight on the back foot and attempts to punch it through the line. He fails to keep it down and plays it straight towards gully. It goes at a rate of knots to Tim Southee who shows excellent reflexes to cup it safely. The deficit for England is 40.
Commentary.Howout: c Tim Southee b Colin de Grandhomme

Commentary.Commentary: Bowls it full and in the line of the stumps, Root brings his bat down and defends it near his pads.
Southee bowls it from round the wicket angle and delivers it on off, Lees stands across the stumps and defends it close to his body.
Fullish and on middle, it's worked to the right of mid on for one.
Fuller and on middle, defended on the leg side.
Outside off, left alone.

Huge shout for an lbw but the umpire stays unmoved. Tim is very excited but fails to convince his skipper for the DRS. A length ball, around off and angling in, Root goes on his toes as he tries to defend. It seems to be bat first but Southee feels it's clipped the back pad first. The replays, later on, show that it indeed was pad first, however, it would have missed the stumps.
Back of a length, around off, Root goes back and defends it to the off side.
Change! Tim Southee is back on. 6-0-29-0 are his figures so far.
FOUR! Short and put away! Lees won't miss out at that pace! The deficit is down to 40 now. Short and outside off, this is cut past point for a boundary.
Outside off, Lees watches it go through to the keeper.
On the fuller side and on middle, this is pushed to mid on.
On middle, Root works it wide of the fielder at mid on for one.
Outside off, a gentle delivery. Left alone.
Fuller and on off, Root looks to drive but it goes off the inner half back to the bowler.
Misfield and a run! Kyle Jamieson gets this one to come back in. Root looks to defend, it goes off the inner half towards square leg where the fielder misfields and a run is taken.

FOUR! Really well played in the end! Length and on off, this lands and moves away. Root opens the face of the bat late and guides it past third slip who gives it a chase and dives but his effort goes in vain.
Back of a length and on off, defended.
Quick run! On middle, this is worked towards mid-wicket for a quick run.

He hurls it across on a good length, on the fifth stump channel, and gets the ball to go straight on. Ollie Pope is stuck on the back foot as he tries to feel for the ball. Ends up getting a faint tickle and the keeper does the rest. Pope looks at his bat in disgust. He has not made an impact in his new role at number 3. England trail by 57 runs.

... DAY 1, SESSION 3 ...

England have safely negotiated the little period before Tea. The Kiwi bowlers have not extracted the same amount of movement that the Englishmen got. Zak Crawley and Alex Lees remained largely untroubled and it's a positive start from England's point of view. The only issue though is the running between the wickets between them and Lees got a life as well when Ajaz Patel missed the opportunity. Two excellent sessions for the hosts and New Zealand will have to try and fight back in the final. The action will resume at 8.30 pm (3 pm GMT).

England and Lees are underway! Swing though for Southee! Fuller, almost goes for a yorker. Ends up bowling a full toss which tails back in from middle, this is jammed towards mid-wicket for a quick run.

England will be pleased with how they began in this innings and how they ended. It is the middle phase which has probably put them behind in the game. It was when the ball got old, they failed to create any sort of problems for Mitchell and Blundell. Still though, those early wickets yesterday and the performace by Broad and Anderson today has kept the visitors in check. Now it is their batters' turn to do their bit. The wicket seems to have improved but it is going to be a test against the new ball, if England play that phase well, they can surely chase this down. New Zealand on the other hand, will hope they can bowl as well or even half as well as they did in the first innings and they should be good. First aim though for England will be to enter Lunch with minimal or no damage and for New Zealand to take a wicket at least. Stay tuned for the chase in a bit.

New Zealand though will be pretty pleased with the score they have! Had they been given 285 when they were reeling at around 50 for 4 they would have surely taken it. They have two men to thank for getting them in the position they are in and they are Mitchell and Blundell. The two added close to 200. One got his ton and the other was unfortunate to miss out on his. They though have given their side the advantage and had it not been for them, the visitors would have been down and out as there was hardly any contribution from the others.

The day though began with Mitchell getting to his ton! Both Blundell and Mitchell began from where they left off yesterday. The second new ball changed things though. Actually that one over from Broad got England back in. Three wickets in it with Broad taking two and a run out. Anderson then got Blundell quickly. The tail though hung around and added a few vital runs which helped the Kiwis take their lead to over 275.

Yet another collapse and one England needed to get back into the game! Yes, New Zealand still have a decent lead, yes, the target is still a stiff one for the hosts but they have given themselves a chance courtesy the performance by their bowlers this morning.

It is reviewed but more in hope. Replays show no bat and then three reds. An outstanding innings from him. Have to feel for him, a lot went on after he got into the 90s and in the end, he misses out on a well-deserved ton.

Pope hits the stumps at the keeper's end and England start celebrating. It is taken upstairs and replays show Colin de Grandhomme is short.

The players make their way out to the middle! The floodlights are on and it is cloudy which means it could be great conditions to bowl in. Tom Blundell and Daryl Mitchell will resume their innings. Stuart Broad to begin. One over to go before the second new ball is available.

EVEN BETTER NEWS! Game to begin at 1130 local (1030 GMT) which is not far away and we have no overs lost today as of now. Yes, all of this can change if the heaves decide to open up yet again but for now though, we are not far away from the first ball of Day 3.
UPDATE - 1110 local (1010 GMT) - GOOD NEWS! The covers are coming off. The rain has stopped but the conditions overhead have not changed. However, we could have some play soon.

UPDATE - 1055 local (0955 GMT) - Well, we might not start on time as the RAIN HAS ARRIVED! The covers are on and it has gotten really dark out there. The floodlights are on too. Let us hope it passes by quickly. The forecast ain't that bad so we can be optimistic about getting some play soon.
A word about the WEATHER! It is cloudy but dry at the moment. The covers are coming off too but rain seems imminent. Keeping our fingers crossed.

New Zealand on the other hand, would just want to bat, bat, bat, assuming the weather does not play a part (which seems highly unlikely) there is a lot of time in this game left. First though, the two batters will be hoping to get to their ton. Both are in their 90s and we are pretty sure England are not going to make the runs they need for it easy to score.

England will need to show a lot of character. It is the Kiwis who have always fought back in this game after being behind but it is now time for the hosts to do so. They have no one but themselves to blame for the position they are in. Do they have the fight left in them? Are we going to see the hosts storm back into the game?

From 56 for 4, the Kiwis managed to end Day 2 at 236 for 4. A staggering 180-run unbeaten stand between Mitchell and Blundell has turned the tide into the visitors' favor completely. Another good session for the Kiwis and they'll feel very safe about their position in the game. England on the other hand, know things can change quite quickly and if they do manage to get a couple of wickets early, they will be right back into it. However, the weather could play a major part in the 3 days to come. The forecast is not the best but we are hoping to get enough play to sneak in a result. Welcome to the coverage of Day 3.

This Test match was slipping away from New Zealand, but they have wrestled back the advantage and are now in the driver's seat. A few odd deliveries misbehaved on the second day, so batting last won't be easy. By no means England are out of this game, but they certainly are on the back foot. How will they respond from here? Do join us on Day 3 at 3.30 pm IST (10 am GMT) to find out. You can tune in early for the build-up. Cheers!

The pitch went flat in the afternoon, didn't offer much movement and zip, and the English bowling also went flat. Their bowling attack doesn't have the pace of a Mark Wood or Jofra Archer, and that in a way exposed their bowling depth. Ben Stokes tried to bowl some short stuff but was dealt with ease, and all in all, England had to sweat hard with the ball, in contrast to Day 1.

Tables have turned! Bowlers dominated Day 1, but the batters found their voice on Day 2. The action though started with six wickets in the morning session, and it appeared that we will be in for a carbon copy of the first day but the pair of Daryl Mitchell and Tom Blundell showed the perfect amount of resolve and fortitude to bail New Zealand out of a precarious situation. They brought calculative aggression in the second half of the second session to put England's bowling at bay. New Zealand have displayed character to bounce back twice in this Test match already - once with the ball and now with the bat. The courageous stand between Mitchell and Blundell has moved the Kiwis into a position of great strength.

End of a fantastic day for the Kiwis! And the two architects of their comeback, Tom Blundell and Daryl Mitchell, are walking back amidst a warm ovation from the Lord's crowd. Their 180-run stand has steered New Zealand out of troubled waters and handed them a lead of 227 runs. Both Tom and Daryl though are going to have a sleepless night, as they are in their 90s, and the famous Lord's honours board will be waiting for them on Saturday.

Down the leg side, tickled away to long leg for one.

Stuart Broad is to operate after the break.

England, on the other hand, did not bowl badly at all but it appears that the pitch has eased out a bit. The zip and the movement are negotiable and the current Kiwi pair showed the correct application. The hosts though would have liked to check the flow of runs which increased in the second half of the afternoon session. It's a pitch where you need to be patient. In the last session on Day 1, patience paid off for the tourists. Will the same happen for England? Do join us at 8.30 pm local (3 pm GMT) to find out.

Finally, a session was ruled by the batters. Just the one wicket lost in it and New Zealand have also managed to score at a decent click. This partnership between Mitchell and Blundell has helped them recover but they would know there is still a long way to go. The away side will hope they can continue the good work in the next session as well and extend their stay.
FOUR! Bang! Poor length from the leggie. Short and wide outside off, turning away, Tom Blundell rocks back and whacks it to sweeper cover for a boundary. That will be Tea on Day 2!
Quicker again, short and on middle, punched from the back foot to short mid-wicket.

Gentle delivery, on a length and wide outside off, Tom Blundell looks to go after it initially but then restrains himself.
This one is on a driving length outside off, Tom Blundell regains his composure and allows it through to the keeper.
A touch short and on off, Tom gets back and forces it to mid on. 'Wait on' is the shout from Blundell.
Around off, defended back.
Play and a miss! Short in length and wide outside off, Tom loses concentration and tries to cut it through the line wiildly but misses.
