Fraction short and wide outside off, Tom stays back and punches it square of the wicket on the off side for a couple again. The 50-run stand comes up! Lead is 98.
Anderson bowls it on a length, around middle and leg, Tom Blundell gets back and tucks it through square leg for a couple of runs.
Another half-tracker from the leggie, around middle, Tom moves back and wrists it through square leg for a single.
Drags his length short and lands it close to off, Tom Blundell this time goes on the back foot and punches it towards mid on.
Loopy and full, around off, Tom walks forward and drives it back to the bowler.
Delivers it very full in length, around leg, Mitchell knocks it down to long on for one.
Flighted again, full and around leg, this time Blundell moves back and works it to square leg for a run.
Extra flight on this one, around middle, Tom Blundell gives the charge to take it on the full and pushes it to mid on.
On off, defended.

Frustrating runs for England! Fuller and on off, this one moves away. Mitchell looks to drive, it goes off the outside edge past the diving backward point fielder who does get a hand to it. Two taken.
On the stumps, Mitchell plays it back to the bowler.
Yet another delivery on off, defended.
Back of a length and on off, blocked.
That could have been close! Tom would have in though. On off, shorter, this is pushed towards cover. He takes off. The fielder has a shy but misses at the bowler's end.
Floats it up on middle, Daryl Mitchell defends it back.
On middle, short. Gets away with it as it is only pulled for one to deep mid-wicket.
On middle, defended.
Tom steps out, and the ball dips at the very end. He looks to drive but it goes off the inner half back to the bowler.
Tossed up, around off, Blundell plays yet another false drive as it goes off the inner half to the leg side.
Flighted and full, outside off, Tom advances down the track but mistimes his drive to mid off.
A single to end! On off, this is pushed to cover for one.
Two more to end the over! On off, this is pushed through covers for a couple.
Shortish and on off, this is pushed to covers.
Two! Batting seems a lot easier now! On the pads, this is worked through mid-wicket for two.
This is a lot wider outside off. Easy leave for the batsman.
That is a good leave on this wicket. A brave one we should say. This lands just around off. It goes on with the angle. Blundell lets it be.
Change of ends for James Anderson.
Flighted up, giving it some air and landing outside off, Daryl Mitchell leaves it alone.
Tossed-up delivery on middle, Tom Blundell flicks it towards square leg for one.
Tossed up outside off with a hint of spin, Tom Blundell blocks it on the off side.
Pushes this one through and on off, this is played with a straight bat.
Another one, nicely tossed up. Blocked out.
Tossed up on off, lands it well. Defended.

A massive moment for Matt Parkinson as he has been handed over the ball. A few days back he was bowling in the Vitality Blast and was called in as a concussion replacement for Jack Leach. He joined the squad last evening and here he is, ready to bowl his first ball in Test cricket.

FOUR! Back to back boundaries from Daryl Mitchell. Fuller and outside off, Daryl Mitchell drives it straight and straight past Ben Stokes. The ball races towards long off for a boundary. This was well timed from Daryl Mitchell.
FOUR! Fuller and straight in the line of the stumps, Daryl Mitchell flicks it through square leg for a boundary.
Length ball down the leg side, Tom Blundell flicks it towards mid-wicket and takes a quick single.
Fuller and outside off, Daryl Mitchell eases it towards covers for one.
Outside off, Daryl Mitchell drives it into the gap at covers and gets a brace.
Goes fuller and outside off, this is eased towards the mid off region.
Back of a length and outside off, Tom Blundell guides it straight towards the fielder at point.
Good-length delivery on middle, Tom Blundell blocks it out solidly.
Touch fuller and on leg, Daryl Mitchell flicks it towards mid-wicket for one.
BEATEN! Another expansive stroke! Fuller and on off, shapes away late. Mitchell looks to go down the ground again but misses. He is looking to attack Anderson.

JUST WIDE AND FOUR! Almost! The extravagant shot got about a wicket. Fuller and on off, this shapes away. Daryl goes for a big one down the ground. This goes off the outside edge past the diving gully fielder and into the third man fence.
On middle, this is worked to mid-wicket.
Fuller and outside off, driven towards covers for one.
Surprise yorker from Ben Stokes, Daryl Mitchell fumbles a bit but manages to block it in the end.
Length ball on off, this is defended towards covers.

FOUR! This is very well played by Daryl Mitchell. Shorter one on middle, Daryl Mitchell plays a hook shot towards backward square leg. The fielder there gave it a good try diving to his right but couldn't get the ball. The ball races behind the fence for a boundary.
On a length and outside off, Daryl Mitchell lets it go towards the keeper.
Length ball on off, swinging away, Daryl Mitchell guides it towards point.

DRINKS! England continue to hold a firm grip on this game! Their bowlers have been brilliant, not conceding runs and taking wickets at regular intervals. New Zealand need a stand, these two have started well but need to go on.
Back of a length and outside off, Tom Blundell jumps a bit and defends it back towards James Anderson.
On a good length and on off, Tom Blundell stays in his crease and blocks it away.
Good-length delivery and on middle, Tom Blundell flicks it towards square leg.
On a good length and outside off, Daryl Mitchell guides it towards point and rotates the strike.
Similar to the last delivery, Daryl Mitchell guards his stumps and lets it go towards the keeper.
On a length and outside off, Daryl Mitchell looks to block it but misses.
James Anderson (6-3-14-1) is back on.
Shorter one on leg, Tom Blundell leaves it alone towards the keeper.
Outside off, Tom Blundell eases it on the off side.
Fuller and on middle, Tom Blundell defends it towards square leg.
Quite wide outside off, on a length, Blundell shoulders arms.
Digs it in short, around off and there is some steep bounce. Blundell swivels and pulls, keeping it down intentionally but finds square leg.
Fuller and on middle, Tom Blundell defends it towards square leg.
Lands it on a length and outside off, holding its line Daryl strides forward and leaves.
Around off, on a length, Daryl Mitchell defends it solidly.

Broad goes wide of the crease and serves a length ball around middle and leg, Mitchell nudges it down to fine leg. The fielder there runs across to his right and puts in a dive to stop it from touching the fence. The umpire gets it checked upstairs and the replays find everything fine. Two runs taken.
That is defended solidly off the front foot.
Back of a length and outside off, Daryl Mitchell shoulders arms.

Shout for an appeal! The typical 'celebrappeal' of Stuart Board but the finger stays down. Inswinger, on a length and around off, Daryl Mitchell tries to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads. Stokes has strong ears, he has heard that and hence is confident that there is no need to take the DRS.
On middle, blocked out.
FOUR! Fuller and outside off, Tom Blundell bends his back knee and drives it through covers for a boundary. Oh, it's a no ball as well. Five runs off this ball.
On a good length and straight on the stumps, Tom Blundell defends it back towards the bowler.
Fuller and on off, this is defended towards point.
Length delivery on the stumps, Tom Blundell works it towards the leg side.
On a length and outside off, Tom Blundell raises his arms to it and lets it go. No ball called.
Touch fuller and on middle, Daryl Mitchell flicks it towards the leg side and takes a quick single. The lead touches 50 now!
Length ball on middle, this is defended back towards the bowler.
Shout for an lbw, a muted one only. The delivery is on a length and around leg, Blundell fails to flick and wears it on his pads. The appeal is turned down.
On a full length and on middle, Tom Blundell blocks it out solidly.
Fuller and on leg, Tom Blundell tries to flick but misses. It takes his pads and rolls away on the leg side.
Length ball outside off, Tom Blundell raises his arms and lets it go towards the keeper.
On a full length, angling it in, Tom Blundell defends it back towards the bowler.
Good-length delivery outside off, Tom Blundell shoulders arms to it.
Fuller and on off, Daryl Mitchell drives it straight towards the fielder at covers.
Touch fuller and on off, this is defended towards the off side.
Outside off, Daryl Mitchell protects his stumps and lets it go towards the keeper.
Touch fuller and on off, driven straight towards the fielder at mid off.
Length ball down the leg side, Tom Blundell flicks it to backward square leg and rotates the strike.
Touch fuller on the stumps, Daryl Mitchell flicks it towards square leg for one.
This is similar to the last delivery, Tom Blundell looks to flick it but misses. A wicket-maiden from Stuart Broad.
Tom Blundell walks in next.

OUT! CONWAY HAS BEEN STRANGLED DOWN THE LEG SIDE! He will be gutted. Looked so solid and this partnership was going along so well but Devon falls to a poor ball. England have strengthened their grip on this game. This is short and slides down the leg side. Conway looks to pull but it takes his gloves and Foakes does the rest. New Zealand are effectively 47 for 4.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Foakes b Stuart Broad

Commentary.Commentary: On a length and outside off, Devon Conway blocks his stumps and leaves the ball towards the keeper.
Touch fuller and outside off, Devon Conway drives it straight towards the fielder at covers.
Good-length delivery and on off, Devon Conway defends it solidly.
Length ball wide outside off, Devon Conway lets it go.
Some issue with the ball. The umpire quickly checks it through the 8-shaped gauge and finds it perfect to continue.
Sticks to his line and delivers straight in the line of the stumps, Daryl Mitchell defends it towards the fielder at mid on.
On off, Devon Conway eases it towards square leg for a single.
Back of a length delivery again, Devon Conway looks to block it but gets a thick inside edge as the ball bounces back and goes towards the keeper.

SUPERB FIELDING! Back of a length and on middle, Daryl Mitchell pulls it through deep square leg. Brilliant fielding by Stuart Broad diving to his left and collecting the ball just before the fence. Single taken. You must have seen many reverse cup catches but this ground fielding is done with a reverse cup action. Broad gets up and his reaction suggests that he has surprised himself with that fielding effort. The crowd loved it and the English players are also clapping for the veteran.
On a good length and on middle, Devon Conway flicks it to square leg and rotates the strike.
Touch fuller down the leg side, Daryl Mitchell flicks it towards mid-wicket for one.
Around off, on a length, defended safely.
Bowls that in-between length, outside off, Conway gets on the back foot and defends it to the off side.
Shaping away from outside off, on a length, Conway covers his stumps and shoulders arms.
Outside off, left alone.
Fuller and on off, driven to covers but not in the gap.
The batter has just watchfully blocked this out.
Full in length and outside off, shaping away late, Mitchell guards his stumps and makes a leave.
Full and on off, angling in, Conway tries to defend but it takes the inner edge and rolls away to square leg. They cross for a run. Lead moves to 43.
Potts dishes out another delivery to be driven. It lands and moves away a bit as Conway allows it through to the keeper.
Too full in length, around off, Conway plays a cracking cover drive but finds the fielder.
Pulls his length back slightly and delivers it outside off, Conway strides forward and defends it down to cover-point.
Fullish and on off, Devon defends it quietly to the leg side. The mid-wicket fielder intervenes and picks up the ball.
Broad pitches it up and around off at 84 mph, Daryl Mitchell drives well but finds the mid on fielder.
Around off, on a length, Daryl Mitchell taps it down to cover-point and lets out a clear shout for no.
Serves it on a length and in the zone outside off, Mitchell covers his sticks and offers no shot.
Targets the off stump with a length delivery, Mitchell goes on the back foot and defends it on the off side.
Hurls across a length ball in the channel outside off, Mitchell lets it go to the keeper.

Beauty! This one lands on a length and close to off, Daryl Mitchell brings down a straight bat, expecting it to curl back in off the seam but it doesn't bend back in enough and beats the outside edge.
Dot to end! On off, blocked.
Three more and the fifty is up for New Zealand. Fuller and on off, this is timed through mid off. Mid on gives the chase, dives and pushes it back in. Saves a run for his side.
EDGY FOUR! Length and on off, this one holds its line. Daryl looks to defend, it goes off the outside edge through gully and into the boundary.
That stays low! Well played in the end! Length and on off, this one skids through. Mitchell gets his bat down in time and blocks.
Yet another delivery outside the off pole. Not played at.
Outside off, left alone.
On off, blocked.
FOUR! Times well! Fuller and around middle, Conway shows the full face of the bat and strokes it down the ground to the long on fence. Good start for the Kiwis after the break.
Outside off, left alone.
NO BALL! Fuller and on off, this is pushed towards mid off for one.
Slightly shorter and on middle, Daryl works it to short leg.
Good length and on off, this lands and holds its line. Mitchell defends it right under his eyes.
Stuart Broad to start the over.
A fuller one to begin the session. It is played to mid off.

We are back for the afternoon session! The England players stride out to the middle and are followed by Conway and Mitchell who will continue their innings. Stuart Broad to start the session. Here we go again...
... DAY 2, SESSION 2 ...

Another session of this Test match has belonged to the bowlers! The Kiwis took a little over six overs to pick the remaining three English wickets, but England didn't waste much time returning the favour. The only difference was that New Zealand picked the tail-end wickets while the Three Lions hunted down the top three. A lead of just nine was gained by the home team but again their bowlers have seized the initiative. The Black Caps are effectively 29 for three and have a mountain to climb. Do join us at 6.10 pm local (12.40 pm GMT) to find out whether they climb or fall down further.
A single to end the session! Angled into middle, this is worked through mid-wicket for one. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 2!
Solid! Angled in on a length and around off, Mitchell plays it back to the bowler.
Bangs it short and outside off, evaded well.
Almost drags it on! On the fuller side yet again, it tails back in once more. Conway looks to drive, but it goes off the inside edge, past the off pole and down to fine leg for one.
Fuller in length and this one comes back in. Conway looks to drive but it goes off the inner half to mid-wicket.
Superb from Potts! Length and on off, Conway defends it right under his eyes.
Good length again and outside off, left alone.
Angled into the middle pole, this is worked to mid-wicket.
A low full toss then on off, Mitchell looks to drive, it goes off the bottom edge towards cover.
A harmless nut, one of the few. Outside off, left alone.

Edged but short! There seems like a wicket on every ball! Length and on off, this lands and moves away. Mitchell looks to defend, this time with soft hands, it goes off the outside edge and lands short of the diving second slip fielder.
That is a beauty! Fuller and around off, this one shapes away. Daryl Mitchell goes for a big booming drive down the ground but is beaten. Realised later he should have left that.
Fuller and tailing back in from off, Conway works it to mid-wicket.
Drop and run! On off, Daryl Mitchell pushes it towards cover for one. He is off the mark.
Shorter one on middle, Daryl Mitchell ducks under it.
On off, defended.
Daryl Mitchell is in next with New Zealand staring down the barrel.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! UltraEdge shows a spike! Latham is gone and takes a review along with him! New Zealand are now in deep trouble. Matthew Potts has another wicket. What a debut he is having! This is a gem of delivery again. Lands it is on a length, around off, it pitches and moves a bit. Latham is on the back foot as he attempts to play inside the line. It goes past the bat, the keeper takes it, and there is an appeal from a few England fielders and the bowler but nothing from the keeper. The umpire though raises his finger. Latham is not sure, he walks up to his partner and then reviews. Time for the replays and it detects a spike as the ball goes past the shoulder of the bat. Big blow to the Black Caps.
Commentary.Howout: c Ben Foakes b Matthew Potts

Commentary.Commentary: On a good length and on off, Devon Conway looks to block it but gets an inside edge as the ball races towards the mid-wicket region. The batters rotate the strike.
Length ball angling it away of off, Devon Conway dosen't bother it.
Length ball on off, Tom Latham defends it towards mid off.
Outside off again, Devon Conway eases it towards the off side and rotates the strike.
On a good length and outside off, Devon Conway looks to drive it but misses. The ball just aired past his bat and goes towards the keeper. This is good bowling from Stuart Broad.
Length ball and on off, Devon Conway again eases it towards the leg side, finds mid-wicket.
Fuller and angling it outside off, Devon Conway defends it towards mid on.
Stuart Broad (4-0-12-0) returns for his second spell.
Touch fuller this time outside off, Tom Latham defends it with soft hands as it rolls to the fielder at point.
Change of length this time. Back of a length outside off, Tom Latham lets it through to the keeper.
Fuller and outside off, Devon Conway flicks it through mid on. The fielder chases it and saves a run for his team. Three runs are taken.
Goes fuller this time and on stumps, Devon Conway defends it back towards the bowler.
Devon Conway is in next.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! That is a huge wicket. Matthew Potts' impressive debut continues and he gets the New Zealand skipper yet again. This is a nothing delivery. Williamson will be very disappointed. This is short and outside off, Williamson looks to punch it from the back foot, but away from his body. He does so with the outer half of his bat and it flies to Bairstow at third slip, who makes no mistake. Another catch for him in this Test match. This dismissal is a bit similar to Root's last evening. New Zealand are effectively 21 for 2. England will look for another one before Lunch.
Commentary.Howout: c Jonny Bairstow b Matthew Potts

Commentary.Commentary: On a length and on middle, this is blocked back towards Matthew Potts.
FOUR! Back of a length and outside off, Tom Latham waits for the ball and punches it through covers for a boundary.
Fuller and outside off, Tom Latham leaves it alone.
Another one outside off, not played at.
Outside off, left alone.
On off, this is pushed towards covers for one.

FOUR! Edgy from Kane Williamson. Back of a length, around off, Kane Williamson pushes gently inside the line and edges it towards second slip. Zak Crawley tries to snap it with his left hand but it drops in front of him before sneaking through the cordon for a boundary. Jonny Bairstow took a similar opportunity in the first innings.
Outside off, Tom Latham leaves this one as well.
Some extra bounce as it angles back into the batter, Tom Latham looks to defend it but gets an inside edge and the ball hits his pads.
Length ball outside off and straightens a bit, Tom Latham shoulders arms to this one.
Quicker and outside off, Tom Latham lets it go.
Sticks to bowling it outside off, Tom Latham leaves it alone.
FOUR! Starts with a short delivery outside off, Tom Latham cuts this one through point for a boundary. This was a well-timed shot from Latham.
Here comes the first bowling change. Matthew Potts is introduced into the attack. Three slips in place.
Solid stuff! Another one on a length and around middle, kept out to safety.
Anderson goes wide of the crease and bowls this one on middle, Williamson stays back and keeps it out.
Goes back to bowling outside off, left alone.
Another one angled into the pads, Kane works it to square leg.
Angled into the pads, Williamson flicks it but to square leg.
Length and on off, blocked.
Shorter in length and on middle, Latham plays it to mid on.
Drop and run! On middle, Williamson looks to defend it with soft hands, it goes towards the leg side for one.
Close leave! Length and outside off, it does come back in. Williamson does not fiddle with it. That did not come back in enough.
Broad angles this one on middle, looking to hit the pad of Williamson. Kane gets his bat down and works it to mid-wicket.

Latham would feel he missed out there! Looking to play the ball really late. This is full and on off, almost a half volley. Latham is late in getting his bat down, and it goes off the bottom half towards covers for one.
Good length and on off, defended.
FOUR! That is wonderful! Sheer timing! Did not look to hit it hard! It is fuller and on off, Williamson shows the full face of the bat and creams it down to the long off fence.
Soft hands! Length and on off, shaping away. Williamson plays it late and right under his eyes. It goes to the 4th slip fielder but on the bounce.
Bangs it short and on middle, Williamson hops and nudges it to mid-wicket.
Yet another delivery outside off, Williamson shoulders arms to this one. The extravagant movement we saw in the first innings seems to have disappeared.
On the fuller side this time, tailing back in from off. Williamson plays it back to the bowler with soft hands.
Good length and on off, Kane Williamson defends it to covers.
There is some issue behind the bowler's arm. The groundsmen quickly get it sorted. Here is Anderson...
Outside off, to end. Easy leave for Latham.
Kiwis are into the lead! Three more for Williamson! Through the off side this time. Shorter and outside off, Williamson gets on top of the bounce and pushes it past point.
Two and the Kiwis only trail by 1 now! Williamson is finally off the mark! Angled into the pads, this is clipped down to fine leg for two.

Angled into the pads, Williamson works it to mid-wicket. England have probably bowled a little too far outside off to Williamson. They need to make him play more as he is not in form. He won't mind the deliveries outside off.
Williamson is yet to get off the mark! Quite watchful so far! Outside off yet again, left alone.
Outside off, Kane Williamson lets it go.
Back of a length around off, angling in, Latham goes back and works it to square leg. Maiden.
In the channel outside off, Tom Latham shows no interest in offering any shot.
Slightly short and on off, Tom stands inside the crease and plays it down to point.
Fuller and on off, blocked confidently.
Angles it in, on a length around off, Latham is on the back foot as he defends it down to the off side.
Lands it on a length and outside off, from round the wicket, Latham leaves.
Inswinger this time, but the line is quite wide outside off to bother the batter. Kane Williamson is not going to chase it.
Angling in a length ball on off, Williamson defends it to the off side.
Dishes out an outswinger, on a length outside off, Williamson allows it through to the keeper.
Gets behind the line of the delivery and blocks it safely onto the pitch.
Fuller and around off, Williamson drives but finds the short cover fielder.
Back of a length, on middle and leg, Latham glances it down to fine leg for a run.
A length delivery on off, defended. Excellent from Anderson, a wicket maiden, not for the first time in this Test match.
Keeps bowling full and in the line of the stumps, Williamson covers the line and blocks.
Fuller and on off, Williamson defends it gently to the leg side.
Slants in a length ball on off, Williamson plays close to his body and defends it down.
Angles it in, on a length around off, Williamson allows the ball to come to him and then defends it with soft hands to point. Looks for a run but it's not available.
Kane Williamson walks out to bat!

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Anderson draws first blood again. A lovely outswinger from the great man. His line is impeccable, just around off and the length is on the fuller side. Will Young responds and rushes across as the fielder (Ben Stokes) comes up with a direct hit at the striker's end. That's all we have from this absorbing Test match. Important points gained by England for the ICC World Test Championship. The second Test match starts on Friday, 10th June 2022 at 3.30 pm IST (10 am GMT) but as usual, our build-up will begin in advance. Until then, it's goodbye and cheers!

Joe Root is the Player of the Match! The former England skipper talks about his hundred and says that it's fantastic and more importantly, they won the game after such a long time. Adds that it's been a tough road for everyone and he has enjoyed this game and looking forward to the rest of the summer. Hopes that they can use this as a way to step forward. Shares that they always get fantastic support at this ground and it's nice to see them get their money back as well. On playing under Ben Stokes, Root replies that the transition has been smooth and mentions that Ben Stokes won England a number of Test matches under his leadership, and it's a great chance for Root to give back to him. Tells that he loves batting and wants to score as many runs as he can and again make England the best Test team.

Ben Stokes, the victorious captain of England, calls it an amazing Test match to be a part of. Tells that regardless of being captain, the first Test of the English summer is always special due to all the buzz and the build-up. Further says that it was a special week and this win makes it even better. On his rapport with Brendon McCullum, Stokes replies that it's going pretty good with him and he has enjoyed the first week working with him. Adds that there is a change of mindset for everyone, this is a great start and he is happy that everybody operated well this week. Stokes mentions that no one had the upper hand at any stage as this game ebbed and flowed. Regarding Root's hundred and 10,000 runs, Stokes calls him Mr Dependable. On the debut of Matthew Potts, Stokes replies that he loved it and he has been tracking his progress in a Durham shirt. Talks about the impact Potts created every time he got the ball and praises him for his amazing attitude. Praises the knocks of Alex Lees and Jonny Bairstow, and is happy with the attitude shown by them. Smiles and adds that seeing Broad and Anderson still running in and delivering for England inspires them.

Kane Williamson, the captain of New Zealand, starts by saying that the game ebbed and flowed the whole time. Tells that it was tough against the new ball but then it changed. Mentions that they came this morning with high hopes and thought there might be some assistance from the overhead conditions but it wasn't to be. Feels that it's about moving on quickly and taking the learnings. Regarding him trying his best to get the ball changed, Williamson replies that it was pretty difficult and he thought if they get it changed, they might get something going. Calls it a fantastic game and it took an incredible knock from Joe Root to take England home. On Root completing 10,000 Test runs, Kane terms it an unbelievable achievement. States that everybody wants to be contributing more and there was a lot of assistance with the harder ball, so the top order will have to work hard. He is looking forward to the next challenge.
Presentation time...

As mentioned earlier, this Test match wasn't a straightforward one. Momentum was no one's friend, and it kept changing sides quicker than the tennis ball does at Roland Garros. England bounced back. Stuart Broad was at the centre of this comeback. His two wickets and then a run out in the same over through Ollie Pope's direct hit stole New Zealand's advantage. At one stage what looked like a lead above 350, remained 276, and the hosts earned themselves a chance to go 1-0 up in the series.

The second day also started with six wickets in the morning session, and we thought, this Test won't see the next day. But as the saying goes, cricket is a game of great uncertainties. Daryl Mitchell and Tom Blundell joined forces to rescue the touring team. Their 195-run stand took the wind out of England's sails, and by the end of Day 2, New Zealand got into the position to dictate terms. Did they do that?

Let's quickly run through the ebbs and flows of the first Test of this English summer. It was expected to be a batting beauty at Lord's, and both skippers had the same thought in mind - to bat first. Kane Williamson had his say, but things didn't go as planned. Although there weren't any demons on the surface, there was just enough juice to extract. The trio of Anderson, Broad and Potts combined to make full use of the conditions and blew away the Kiwis inside two sessions. New Zealand though didn't sit back regretting and retorted by picking seven English wickets by Stumps on Day 1.

England have done it! They've won this roller-coaster of a Test match. With 61 needed this morning, and five wickets in the tank, the hosts made sure there were no hiccups. The start to the chase was a bit iffy for the hosts, but once Ben Stokes got a life (bowled off a no ball on 1), he and Root constructed a 90-run stand to make things smooth. The former skipper then allied with Ben Foakes to raise an unbeaten match-winning century stand to take England home. Root also went on to complete his maiden century in the fourth innings of a Test match and notched up 10,000 Test runs - only the second Englishman to achieve this feat after Sir Alastair Cook.

Joe Root leads everyone off the park! A great knock. It's a huge ovation for him. No drama in the morning. England stayed focused. New Zealand didn't get the movement they needed and looked lacklustre. Kane Williamson tried hard to convince the umpires to change the ball but in vain. Interestingly, they had one ball changed before as well, and after that, the degree of movement they got was a lot lesser than the previous time. These little things matter sometimes.

FOUR! Here is the winning shot! Joe Root has done it. New era, new England, a new captain and they start with a thumping win over New Zealand. FOUR! Finds the gap at last! A touch short in length and outside off, Root stays on the back foot and delicately guides it through the gap between gully and wide slip for a boundary.

The morning session is set to begin on time, although it remains heavily overcast. The New Zealand players stride out to the middle. Followed by Joe Root and Ben Foakes who walk out to continue with their blade. It will be Tim Southee to start with the ball. Here we go...

Promising signs! The forecast isn't too great and the overhead conditions are gloomy but currently, it's not raining and the hover cover is not covering the pitch. Let's hope it stays this way and we get going on time. You already are aware of the equation needed, it looks quite straightforward but just for your reference, New Zealand lost 6 wickets yesterday for just 34 runs. If the Kiwi bowlers manage to strike the right chords and the overcast conditions come to their assistance, this little phase left in this Test match could become enthralling.

New Zealand, on the flip side, have a casualty in the form of Colin de Grandhomme after he limped off the field on Day 3. It is suspected that he has suffered a tear in his heel and we would get a better picture once the scheduled MRI scan is done. Coming to the game, the Kiwis would still believe that they can pull a rabbit out of the hat if they are able to get rid of Root early. Is there another twist left in this tale? Stick around to find out who will take the lead in this series.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 4 of the first Test match between England and New Zealand. This match has surely moved briskly and it looks like England have their noses in front thanks to their former skipper, Joe Root. England are in contention of winning the game even after Kyle Jamieson's outstanding effort. The home side would hope that their lower-middle order along with Root is able to kick start their summer with a victory. Well, all this can happen only if the rain gods show some mercy.
... Day 4, Session 1...

The Kiwis just looked tired towards the end! Their bowlers did not bowl with the same energy, there were a few misfields too. They just had no answers to the batting of Root, Stokes of Foakes. However, they'll come all fresh on Day 4's morning, they would know a wicket and they'll be into the bowlers. The question is, who will get it for them? Day 4 promises to be a cracking on. Do join us for all the acion. Till then, take care and goodbye!

In reply, they were in big, big trouble at 69 for 4. It could have been worse had Colin not overstepped. Since then though, it has been all England. The skipper and the former skipper played brilliantly. The two added 90 before Stokes fell. Root though continued and along with Foakes has added another 50-run stand. The two have turned the game into England's favor.

End of a hard, fought day of Test cricket and we believe, England have their noses in front. A round of applause for England's former captain as he makes his way back into the dug out. We asked if England have it in them to show some character and fight to get back in the game and they surely do. First, they made quick work of the remaining wickets in the first session and kept the visitors in tact.

It was the Jamieson show as he got the better of Bairstow and Crawley. Boult also chipped in with a wicket. However, New Zealand will know it is important to break this stand. The pitch is offering something for the bowlers but it is still a good one to bat on. New Zealand need to continue to hit the right areas and they will be eager for a couple of wickets after the break. England on the other hand, would hope these two can build a decent stand and lay the platform for their side. A very interesting session awaits. Do join us in sometime.

Excellent session of Test cricket! Have to say it has been England's morning. After pickings wickets in a flurry this morning, the hosts kept England well in-tact. They had just below an hour to play out before Lunch. Lees and Crawley began brilliantly. They played their shots and Lees was scoring freely. Kyle Jamieson it was though again who got the opening breakthrough for his side. Since then, the runs have dried out and New Zealand have started to cause problems too.
